{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504989","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504989"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:24:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:24:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2394"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2394"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.86,0.04,0.06,0.03,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2394"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62846"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2394"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2394"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48296"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"8840"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1584"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1624"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19128"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19953"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62846"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one-hour history of right eye pain, tearing and foreign body sensation. He was grinding metal without eye protection when he felt something strike his eye. He attempted to irrigate the eye at home without relief. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 75/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. The right eye shows excessive tearing and blepharospasm. Visual acuity is 6/6 bilaterally. Gross examination with a torch reveals no obvious foreign body.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fluorescein dye examination","Instil mydriatic drops","Orbital X-ray","Computed tomography scan","Tonometry"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a high-risk mechanism for corneal injury, with symptoms strongly suggestive of corneal abrasion or retained foreign body. \u003Cstrong\u003EFluorescein dye examination\u003C/strong\u003E is essential as the first-line investigation to identify corneal epithelial defects that may not be visible on gross examination. The fluorescein will pool in any epithelial defect and fluoresce under cobalt blue light, revealing the extent and location of corneal injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInstilling mydriatic drops\u003C/strong\u003E may be used to facilitate examination of the posterior eye or for therapeutic purposes once injury is confirmed. However, in this case, with normal visual acuity and no signs suggesting posterior segment involvement, dilation is not required as the first investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrbital X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if there is concern for an intraocular foreign body, but should not be the first investigation. It would be considered after a thorough examination of the anterior segment.  Of note as well, a MRI would be contraindicated in this patient due to the metal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography scan\u003C/strong\u003E provides detailed imaging of orbital structures but is reserved for cases where there is suspicion of penetrating injury or retained metallic foreign body not visible on examination.  This would not be the first investigation for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETonometry\u003C/strong\u003E measures intraocular pressure and is commonly used in glaucoma assessment. While it may be part of a complete eye examination, it is not the priority in acute trauma where corneal injury is suspected, and the procedure itself could potentially worsen a corneal injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter fluorescein examination, management may include removal of any identified foreign body, topical antibiotics to prevent infection, and cycloplegic agents for comfort. Metal foreign bodies require careful examination as they may cause rust rings and deeper injury.  Ophthalmology review may be required if there is evidence of penetrating injury or if a rust ring is present.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fluorescein examination is mandatory in any suspected corneal injury or foreign body to identify corneal epithelial defects.","History of high-velocity particles (grinding, drilling) should raise suspicion for penetrating eye injury."],"references":["Wipperman JL, Dorsch JN. Evaluation and management of corneal abrasions. Am Fam Physician. 2013 Jan 15;87(2):114-20. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2013/0115/p114.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48296"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2394"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48296","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48296"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-18T23:31:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-18T23:33:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2394"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62846"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tag